{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"luetkemj","description":"Change Is Good","author":"mark luetke"}},"markdownRemark":{"excerpt":"Last checkin I was on page 7 of the orange journal. That's been archived and I am now on 204 of the yellow journal. 449 pages in 76 days.â€¦","html":"<p>Last checkin I was on page 7 of the orange journal. That's been archived and I am now on 204 of the yellow journal. 449 pages in 76 days. 5.9 pages a day. The pace has quickened.</p>\n<p>Last update I was working on Aglet. I haven't really touched it since then. I was thinking about how I used to make a lot comics. And how so much of my energy was spent convincing myself it was worth the effort. It was always just felt like so much work. This isn't to say that making comics was worth the effort or anything just that some part of me fought it. With code I very rarely find myself fighting it. With Aglet I think of all the infrasctructure I was implementing just to get to the fun parts of procedural generation.</p>\n<p>That's when it hit me. There is an entire genre of video games that focuses almost exclusively on the very things I found the most fun with Aglet. It's a project that never feels like work. Another hobby, yes. Another time sink that provides no income. But it does bring joy and learning and that's enough I think.</p>\n<p>And so began this deep dive into the world of Roguelikes.</p>\n<p>Initially I just sat down and wrote something. A white square I could move on a stage with green goblins I could bump into. The goal was to be the last the to die. I have never won. But I learned a lot and you gotta start somewhere.</p>\n<p>Snerv | <a href=\"https://luetkemj.github.io/snerv/\">PLAY</a> | <a href=\"https://github.com/luetkemj/snerv\">source</a></p>\n<p><a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/653428e39f54328fd5fda9da4a58dc0d/0d52c/CA-191117-snerv.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=